\begin_layout Section
Cutting Plane Methods
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Cutting-Plane-Methods"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of this chapter is to present some polynomial-time algorithms for
 convex optimization.
 These algorithms use the knowledge of the function in a minimal way, essentiall
y by querying the function value and knowing some (weak) bounds on its support/v
alue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a continuously differentiable convex function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:first_order"

\end_inset

 shows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(y)\geq f(x)+\left\langle \nabla f(x),y-x\right\rangle \text{ for all }y.\label{eq:sub_grad_def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 be any minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\geq f(x^{*})\geq f(x)+\left\langle \nabla f(x),x^{*}-x\right\rangle .
\]

\end_inset

Therefore, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \nabla f(x),x^{*}-x\right\rangle \leq0$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 lies in a halfspace 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 with normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Roughly speaking, this shows that each gradient computation cuts the set
 of possible solutions in half.
 In one dimension, this allows us to do a binary search to minimize convex
 functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rn$
\end_inset

, binary search still works.
 In this chapter, we will cover several ways to do this binary search.
 All of them follow the same framework, called the 
\emph on
cutting plane method
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, cutting plane methods solves the following class of problems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prob:abstract_convex_problem"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finding a point in a convex set
\end_layout

\end_inset

Given a convex set 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subset\Rn$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin K$
\end_inset

, we can find a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x)^{\top}(y-x)\leq0\text{ for all }y\in K.
\]

\end_inset

Our goal is to find some 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in K$
\end_inset

 or prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol K\leq\epsilon^{n}$
\end_inset

 using as few calls to 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 as possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
When apply to convex functions, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=\nabla f(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be the set of minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 In chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:vol2val"

\end_inset

, we relate the problem of proving 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol K$
\end_inset

 is small and the problem of finding an approximate minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this framework, we maintain a convex set 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 that contains the set 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Each iteration, we compute 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x^{(k)})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 chosen based on 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k)}$
\end_inset

.
 The guarantee of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 lies in the halfspace 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{(k)}=\{y:g(x^{(k)})^{\top}(y-x^{(k)})\leq0\}$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subset H^{(k)}\cap E^{(k)}.$
\end_inset

 The algorithm continues by choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k+1)}$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{(k)}\cap E^{(k)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

