\begin_layout Section
Ellipsoid Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first start by explaining the simplest algorithm, the Ellipsoid method.
 We maintain an ellipsoid
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E^{(k)}\defeq\{x\in\Rn:\ (x-x^{(k)})^{\top}\left(A^{(k)}\right)^{-1}(x-x^{(k)})\leq1\}
\]

\end_inset

that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 After we compute 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x^{(k)})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 via (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Hk"

\end_inset

), we define 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k+1)}$
\end_inset

 to be the smallest volume ellipsoid containing 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k)}\cap H^{(k)}$
\end_inset

.
 The key observation is that the volume of the ellipsoid 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 decreases by 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\Theta(\frac{1}{n})$
\end_inset

 every iteration.
 This volume property holds for any halfspace through the center of the
 current ellipsoid (not only for the one whose normal is the gradient),
 a property we will exploit in the next chapter.
\end_layout

