\begin_layout Section
Center of Gravity Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Ellipsoid method, we used an ellipsoid as the current set, and its
 center as the next query point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the center of gravity method, we start with any bounded convex set containing
 a minimizer, e.g., a large enough cube, and the set maintained is simply
 the intersection of all halfspaces used so far.
 The query point will be the center of gravity (or barycenter) of the current
 set.
 The measure of progress will once again be the volume (or more precisely,
 volume radius) of the current set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is clear that the volume can only decrease in each iteration.
 But at what rate? The following classical theorem shows that the volume
 of the convex body decreases by at least a 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\frac{1}{e}$
\end_inset

 factor when using the exact center of gravity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:Grunbaum"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a convex body in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 with center of gravity 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be any halfspace containing 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vol(K\cap H)\ge\left(\frac{n}{n+1}\right)^{n}\vol(K).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the RHS is at least 
\begin_inset Formula $1/e$
\end_inset

.
 We prove the theorem later in this chapter.
 Unfortunately, computing the center of gravity even of a polytope is #P-hard
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rademacher2007approximating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For the purpose of efficient approximations, it is important to establish
 a stable version of the theorem that does not require an exact center of
 gravity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that a nonnegative function is logconcave if its logarithm is concave,
 i.e., for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\lambda x+(1-\lambda)y)\ge f(x)^{\lambda}f(y)^{1-\lambda}.
\]

\end_inset

We refer to Sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Logconcave-functions"

\end_inset

 for some background on logconcave functions.
 A distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
isotropic
\emph default
 if the mean of a random variable drawn from the distribution is zero and
 the covariance is the identity matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The randomized center of gravity method defined as follows: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{1},\ldots,y^{N}$
\end_inset

 be uniform random points from 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 and define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{(k)} & =\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}y^{i},\\
E^{(k+1)} & =E^{(k)}\cap H^{(k)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

To prove its convergence, we will use a robust version of the following
 classical theorem of Grunbaum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:grun-1"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Robust Grunbaum
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be an isotropic logconcave distribution, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\E_{x\sim p}x=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\E_{x\sim p}x^{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\R^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\R$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\P_{x\sim p}(x^{\top}\theta\geq t)\geq\frac{1}{e}-t.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By taking the marginal with respect to the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, we can assume the distribution is one-dimensional.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P(t)=\P_{x\sim p}(x^{\top}\theta\le t)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $P(t)$
\end_inset

 is the convolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{(-\infty,0]}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, it is logconcave (Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:marginal"

\end_inset

).
 By some limit arguments, we can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $P(-M)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P(M)=1$
\end_inset

 for some large enough 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 (to be rigorous, we do the proof below for finite 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and a RHS 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon(M)$
\end_inset

 instead of zero, then take the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $M\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\E_{x\sim p}x=0$
\end_inset

, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-M}^{M}tP'(t)\,dt=0
\]

\end_inset

Integration by parts gives that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-M}^{M}P(t)dt=M$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $P(t)$
\end_inset

 is increasing logconcave, if 
\begin_inset Formula $P(0)$
\end_inset

 is too small, it would make 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-M}^{M}P(t)dt$
\end_inset

 too small.
 To be precise, since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is logconcave, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\log P(t)\geq-\log P(0)-\frac{P'(0)}{P(0)}t.
\]

\end_inset

Or we simply write 
\begin_inset Formula $P(t)\leq P(0)e^{\alpha t}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\int_{-M}^{M}P(t)dt\leq\int_{-\infty}^{\frac{1}{\alpha}}P(0)e^{\alpha t}dt+\int_{1/\alpha}^{M}1dt=\frac{eP(0)}{\alpha}+M-\frac{1}{\alpha}.
\]

\end_inset

This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $P(0)\geq\frac{1}{e}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Next, Lemma 
