 readily gives the following guarantee for convex optimization, again using
 volume radius as the measure of progress.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a convex function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rn$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(0)}$
\end_inset

 be any initial set and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subset E^{(0)}$
\end_inset

 be any convex set.
 Suppose that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E^{(0)}$
\end_inset

, we can find a nonzero vector 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(y)\geq f(x)\text{ for any }y\text{ such that }g(x)^{\top}(y-x)\geq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Then, for the center of gravity method with 
\begin_inset Formula $N=10n$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\E\min_{i=1,2,\cdots k}f(x^{(i)})-\min_{y\in\Omega}f(y)\leq\left(\frac{\vol(E^{(0)})}{\vol(\Omega)}\right)^{\frac{1}{n}}\left(0.95\right)^{\frac{k}{n}}\left(\max_{z\in\Omega}f(z)-\min_{x\in\Omega}f(x)\right)\enspace.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we give a geometric proof Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Grunbaum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that one can modify the proof of Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:grun-1"

\end_inset

 to get another proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Without loss of generality, assume that the center of gravity of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is the origin and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the halfspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x:\:x_{1}\le0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 For each point 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\R$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)=K\cap\left\{ x:\ x_{1}=t\right\} $
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-dimensional slice of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=t$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

 as the radius of the 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-dimensional ball with the same 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-dimensional volume as 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The goal of the proof is to show that the smallest possible halfspace volume
 is achieved for a cone by a cut perpendicular to its axis.
 In the first step, we will symmetrize 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as follows: replace each cross-section 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)$
\end_inset

 by a ball of the same volume, centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,0,\ldots,0)^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that the resulting rotationally symmetric body is convex.
 To see this, note that all we have to show is that the radius function
 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

 is concave.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t\in\R,$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, we have by convexity of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda A(s)+(1-\lambda)A(t)\subseteq A(\lambda s+(1-\lambda)t)
\]

\end_inset

and by the Brunn-Minkowski theorem (Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Brunn-Minkowski"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $A(s),A(t)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vol_{n-1}(A(\lambda s+(1-\lambda)t))^{\frac{1}{n-1}}\ge\lambda\vol_{n-1}(A(s))^{\frac{1}{n-1}}+(1-\lambda)\vol_{n-1}(A(t))^{\frac{1}{n-1}}.
\]

\end_inset

From this and the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

, it follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r(\lambda s+(1-\lambda)t)\ge\lambda r(s)+(1-\lambda)r(t)
\]

\end_inset

as desired.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Next consider the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}=K\cap\left\{ x:\:x_{1}\le0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We replace this subset with a cone 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 having the same base 
\begin_inset Formula $A(0)$
\end_inset

 and apex at some point along the 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1}$
\end_inset

 axis so that the volume of the cone is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol(K_{1}).$
\end_inset

 Using the concavity of the radial function, this transformation can only
 decrease the center of gravity along 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, proving a lower bound on the transformed body 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

 will give a lower bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 So assume we do this and the center of gravity is the origin.
 Next, extend the cone to the right, so that it remains a rotational cone,
 and the volume in the positive halfspace along 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol(K\setminus K_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 Once again, the center of gravity can only move to the left, and so the
 volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

 can only decrease by this transformation.
 At the end we have shown that the lower bound for any convex body follows
 by proving for a rotational cone with axis along the normal to the halfspace.
 Now we compute the volume ratio:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\vol(K_{1})}{\vol(K)}=\left(\frac{n}{n+1}\right)^{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In later chapters we will see how to implement each iteration of the center
 of gravity method in polynomial time.
 Computing the exact center of gravity is #P-hard even for a polytope 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rademacher2007approximating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but we can find an arbitrarily close approximation in randomized polynomial
 time via sampling.
 The method generalizes to certain noisy computation models, e.g., when the
 oracle reports a function value that is within a bounded additive error,
 i.e., a noisy function oracle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will also see that the iteration complexity of the center of gravity
 method, 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n)$
\end_inset

 iterations, is asymptotically optimal.
\end_layout

